<title>Equation of Parabolas</title>

<p><alert>I: Equation of a parabola whose axis is parallel to the <em>y</em>-axis</alert>:</p>
<p>A parabola whose axis is parallel to <em><alert>y</alert></em>-axis is called <alert>vertical parabola</alert>. A vertical parabola is either open upward (as in Figure 4.13 (a) ) or open downward (as in Figure 4.13 (b)).</p>
<p>Let <em>p</em> be the distance from vertex V(<em>h,k</em>) to the focus F of the parabola, i.e.,<alert>|</alert>VF<alert>|</alert> = <em>p</em>. Then, by the definition, F is located <em>p</em> units above V if the parabola opens upward and it is located <em>p</em> units below V if the parabola opens downward as indicated on Figure 4.13(a) and (b), respectively. To determine the desired equation, we first consider the case when the parabola opens upward.</p>
<p>Therefore, considering a vertical parabola with vertex V(<em>h,k</em>) that opens upward (Figure 4.13a), its focus is at F(<em>h, k+p</em>). ⇒ The equation of its directrix is <em>y = k−p.</em></p>
<p>Then, for any point P(<em>x,y</em>) on the parabola, <alert>|</alert>PF<alert>|</alert> is equal to the distance between P and the directrix if and only if</p>
<p><image source="/media/png72/imageC2280.png" /></p>
<p>Upon simplification, this becomes</p>
